    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2427995001" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2427995001" />
    <a title="Ailsa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6117156-ailsa"><img alt="Ailsa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442286271p2/6117156.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2427995001?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ailsa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ailsa" href="/user/show/6117156-ailsa">Ailsa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2427995001" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12205796967285574521"><b> Love&apos;s supposed to be something ideal and noble, whereas in practice it&apos;s just a sordid matter that degrades us to the level of pigs... nature didn&apos;t make it vile and embarrassing for no reason.&quot;</b><br/><br/>Tolstoy was a weird guy. <br/><br/>This is him in PEAK spiritual crisis mode.<br/><br/>His main argument was that even within marriage sex is immoral. What about reproduction? Kids are the worst. Peasants need to have children to look after them but it is pure selfishness for the rich to have them. Humans have sex even whe</span>
  <span id="freeText12205796967285574521" style="display:none"><b> Love's supposed to be something ideal and noble, whereas in practice it's just a sordid matter that degrades us to the level of pigs... nature didn't make it vile and embarrassing for no reason."</b><br /><br />Tolstoy was a weird guy. <br /><br />This is him in PEAK spiritual crisis mode.<br /><br />His main argument was that even within marriage sex is immoral. What about reproduction? Kids are the worst. Peasants need to have children to look after them but it is pure selfishness for the rich to have them. Humans have sex even when pregnant which is against nature. Arranged marriages are better. A woman's whole education is geared toward trapping a man. They're basically prostitutes. As men have all the privileges in law and society, women exploit their 'sensuality' in revenge. Doctors? Terrible, all quacks. They promote the idea that it is healthy for boys to have carnal appetites. Also contraception? For a woman's health? Foolish and unnecessary. <br /><br />The first three quarters of this novella are a polemic essay in disguise. The last part is taut and well drawn, more like the Tolstoy of <i>Anna Karenina</i> and <i>War and Peace</i>. <br /><br />In any case, if I was Tolstoy's wife, I would have stabbed him repeatedly with a rusty knife for publishing this. Unintentionally incredibly entertaining. Recommend, if you want to read something short and kooky while looking like serious reader of Russian classics. <br /><br />Note: my translation by David McDuff was noticeably odd. Do Russians really say "we had a dickens of a job"(51)? ("We had a Gogol of a time getting a parking spot") Was Tolstoy sloppy enough to use the phrase "vile and embarrassing" 4 times in five lines? Another glaring error on page 92: "I haven't noticed anything except you're behaving like a flirt." "Oh if you're going to start swearing like a cabby" I very much doubt 'flirt' was used in the original text. <br /><br /><b>"We were like two prisoners in the stocks, hating each other, yet fettered to each other by the same chain, poisoning each other's lives and trying not to be aware of it."</b><br />.<br />.<br />.<br />"Education leads to nothing but a lot of silliness." 29<br /><br />"Never trust a horse in the paddock or a wife in the home." 31<br /><br />"Loving the same man or woman all your life - why, that's like supposing the same candle could last you all your life." 34<br /><br />"I lived the sort of life all men do - a life of debauchery." 37<br /><br />"a man who has had several women for the sake of his pleasure is no longer a normal person but one who has been spoiled for all time - a fornicator." 41<br /><br />"I can think of several girls from the higher social circles whose parents enthusiastically married them off to syphilitics." 42<br /><br />"Women know perfectly well that the most elevated love - the most 'poetic', as we call it - depends not on moral qualities but on physical proximity and also on things like hairstyle, or the colour and cut of a dress." 44<br /><br />"At a rule, we may say that while short term prostitutes are generally looked down upon, long term prostitutes are treated with respect." 45<br /><br />"nowadays a woman is like a slave in a market or a piece of bait for a trap." 48<br /><br />"The type of education women receive will always correspond to the way men see them" 63<br /><br />"A honeymoon is an embarrassing, shameful, loathsome, pathetic business, and most of all it is tedious, unbearably tedious!" 52<br /><br />"You'll notice that the animals copulate with one another only when it's possible for them to produce offspring; but the filthy king of nature will do it any time, just so long as it gives him pleasure. More than that he elevates this monkey pastime into the pearl of creation, into love." 62<br /><br />"Children are a torment, nothing more." 68<br /><br />"we went to live in the town. Life's more bearable for unhappy people there." 76<br /><br />"who is it that is constantly putting a brake on humanity's forward development? Women."62<br /><br />"I wanted her to not want what she couldn't help wanting." 106</span>
  <a data-text-id="12205796967285574521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


